│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                              │
│                                                                          │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                          │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                              │
│ The incorrect transformation removes the final fabs from "fabs(select    │
│ ...)" yielding just the select result. Alive2 shows this is wrong for a  │
│ negative subnormal input. InstSimplify simplified "fabs %sel" to "%sel"  │
│ by concluding the sign bit of %sel is known to be zero (non-negative).   │
│ That decision hinges on computeKnownFPSignBit, which relies on           │
│ computeKnownFPClass on the select, which in turn uses fcmpImpliesClass   │
│ to interpret the select condition "fcmp ogt (fabs x), +0.0" as filtering │
│ the result's class.                                                      │
│                                                                          │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                  │
│ opt with --debug-only=instsimplify shows the pass replaced the final     │
│ fabs with the select (%abs2 removed, ret %sel). This simplification      │
│ occurs via InstructionSimplify::simplifyUnaryIntrinsic(), specifically:  │
│   case Intrinsic::fabs:                                                  │
│     if (computeKnownFPSignBit(Op0, Q) == false)                          │
│       return Op0;                                                        │
│ So, computeKnownFPSignBit(Op0) returned false (sign bit known zero) for  │
│ Op0 = %sel.                                                              │
│                                                                          │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                  │
│ computeKnownFPClass for a Select tries to deduce class masks from the    │
│ select condition. Our condition is "fcmp ogt fabs(x), +0.0".             │
│ Semantically, ordered-greater-than of fabs(x) against +0.0 is true iff x │
│ is non-zero and not NaN. That includes negative subnormals/normals.      │
│ Therefore the true branch mask must include negative classes. However,   │
│ GenericFloatingPointPredicateUtils::fcmpImpliesClass mishandles this     │
│ pattern when RHS is +0.0 and LHS is fabs(x). In the IsPositiveRHS path   │
│ with IsFabs, it transforms class sets via inverse_fabs and then maps OGt │
│ to a ClassesGE mask that does not include negative classes, leading      │
│ ValueTracking to conclude the true branch (LHS = x) is non-negative.     │
│ This causes computeKnownFPSignBit to return false, and InstSimplify      │
│ eliminates fabs incorrectly.                                             │
│                                                                          │
│ Thus, the bug is in GenericFloatingPointPredicateUtils.h: the mask       │
│ computation for the case "fcmp ogt fabs(x), +0.0" must be special-cased  │
│ to yield MaskIfTrue = ~fcZero & ~fcNan (all non-zero, any sign), and     │
│ MaskIfFalse = fcZero | fcNan.                                            │
│                                                                          │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                               │
│ Edit file llvm/include/llvm/IR/GenericFloatingPointPredicateUtils.h      │
│ around the handling of IsPositiveRHS with IsFabs (lines ~360-410). Add   │
│ explicit handling when RHS is +0.0 for ordered/unsigned comparisons:     │
│ - For fabs(x) ogt +0.0: return {Src, ~fcZero & ~fcNan, fcZero | fcNan}.  │
│ - For fabs(x) oge +0.0: true for any non-NaN, so return {Src, ~fcNan,    │
│ fcNan}.                                                                  │
│ - For fabs(x) olt +0.0: false (no magnitude less than zero), so return   │
│ {Src, fcNone, fcAllFlags}.                                               │
│ - For fabs(x) ole +0.0: true exactly for zeros (non-NaN zeros), so       │
│ return {Src, fcZero, ~fcZero | fcNan}.                                   │
│ - For unordered variants, invert appropriately.                          │
│ This ensures the true-branch mask includes negative classes for ogt,     │
│ preventing ValueTracking from concluding non-negativity.                 │
│                                                                          │
│ Concrete change (at lines 360-410): inside the "else if (IsPositiveRHS)" │
│ block, after computing ClassesGE/ClassesLE and before applying           │
│ inverse_fabs, insert a special-case branch:                              │
│   if (IsFabs && RHSClass == fcPosZero) {                                 │
│     switch (Pred) {                                                      │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_OGT:                                             │
│       return {Src, ~fcZero & ~fcNan, fcZero | fcNan};                    │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_OGE:                                             │
│       return {Src, ~fcNan, fcNan};                                       │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_OLT:                                             │
│       return {Src, fcNone, fcAllFlags};                                  │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_OLE:                                             │
│       return {Src, fcZero, ~fcZero | fcNan};                             │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_UGT:                                             │
│       // unordered greater-than: true for non-zero or NaN                │
│       return {Src, (~fcZero) , fcZero};                                  │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_UGE:                                             │
│       // unordered greater-equal: true for non-NaN or NaN (always true)  │
│       return {Src, fcAllFlags, fcNone};                                  │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_ULT:                                             │
│       // unordered less-than: true for NaN only                          │
│       return {Src, fcNan, ~fcNan};                                       │
│     case FCmpInst::FCMP_ULE:                                             │
│       // unordered less-equal: true for zero or NaN                      │
│       return {Src, fcZero | fcNan, ~(fcZero | fcNan)};                   │
│     default:                                                             │
│       break;                                                             │
│     }                                                                    │
│   }                                                                      │
│ Then proceed with existing logic for other RHS.                          │
│                                                                          │
│ Note: The unordered cases above follow the semantics of unordered        │
│ predicates including NaN. If preferred, they can be derived by inverting │
│ the ordered cases per existing code style.                               │
│                                                                          │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                           │
│ By correcting the class-mask deduction for "fcmp ogt fabs(x), +0.0",     │
│ ValueTracking will no longer incorrectly assert that the select's true   │
│ branch is non-negative. Consequently, computeKnownFPSignBit(%sel) will   │
│ be indeterminate (or true for some paths), preventing InstSimplify from  │
│ removing the final fabs. This fixes the miscompile demonstrated by the   │
│ reproducer and aligns class reasoning with the semantics of fabs and     │
│ ordered comparisons with zero.                                           │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                          │
